WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:08.650 --> 00:00:19.070
The process of making is the point of it.
This needs to be a kind of ballet.

00:00:19.070 --> 00:00:30.890
&gt;&gt; If anybody can copy [indistinct], it's
not art.

00:00:30.890 --> 00:00:32.369
[violin]

00:00:32.369 --> 00:00:44.370
&gt;&gt; There's no carving in wood or in stone
or knots on a rug that are going to look anything

00:00:44.370 --> 00:00:51.120
near like what pleats do when they express
a line.

00:00:51.120 --> 00:00:53.850
&gt;&gt; Lots of people talk about the reality of
a [indistinct] elephant in origami.

00:00:53.850 --> 00:00:58.900
Does it look real?
Does it look like an elephant?

00:00:58.900 --> 00:01:04.679
But, it's a piece of paper, and, of course,
it can't look like an elephant.

00:01:04.679 --> 00:01:09.110
&gt;&gt; I think, at heart, one of the things that
makes us human -- that's both our strength

00:01:09.110 --> 00:01:15.070
and our weakness -- is a need to change things.
It's also the heart of the appeal of origami,

00:01:15.070 --> 00:01:20.580
exploring the surprising magic of just how
far you can change that square only by folding

00:01:20.580 --> 00:01:21.580
it.

00:01:21.580 --> 00:01:27.120
&gt;&gt; What are the limits -- the physical limits
 -- of this art form?

00:01:27.120 --> 00:01:29.400
&gt;&gt; When you put a crease in the paper, you're
essentially changing the memory of that piece.

00:01:29.400 --> 00:01:36.390
&gt;&gt; Origami is just a way to get your hands
dirty with math.

00:01:36.390 --> 00:01:42.090
It becomes your laboratory for doing mathematics.

00:01:42.090 --> 00:01:47.740
&gt;&gt; Whenever there's a need in the industry
to take a flat sheet and somehow make it smaller,

00:01:47.740 --> 00:01:51.460
there is potential for origami to have an
application.

00:01:51.460 --> 00:01:54.930
&gt;&gt; In science, this is the most creative you
can be.

00:01:54.930 --> 00:02:00.390
We are artists whether we do science or whether
we build sculpture.

